18:26.232 --> 18:29.068
President and advisor.

18:29.277 --> 18:32.530
Harmonious and productive.

18:32.756 --> 18:35.551
Close and special.

18:35.757 --> 18:37.884
You... and I.

19:09.770 --> 19:11.146
Hey, P.J.

19:11.249 --> 19:13.126
What are you doing here
in the boys' locker room?

19:13.251 --> 19:14.710
I've come to see
the star quarterback

19:14.859 --> 19:16.110
before the big game.

19:16.252 --> 19:18.629
But what if Coach Henderson walks in?

19:18.774 --> 19:21.276
Oh, that's OK.
I took care of him.

19:21.471 --> 19:23.139
So, uh, what you reading?

19:23.254 --> 19:26.048
I'm just reviewing my playbook.

19:26.255 --> 19:28.591
I have a playwe can practice.

19:28.778 --> 19:30.196
You be quarterback.

19:30.300 --> 19:32.427
I'll be tight end.

19:43.305 --> 19:46.141
You know,
Coca-Cola is by far

19:46.306 --> 19:49.142
the world's number one soft drink.

19:57.833 --> 19:59.167
Paul.

19:59.268 --> 20:00.186
Aah!

20:06.835 --> 20:08.837
Aah! Aaahhh!

20:08.967 --> 20:10.677
Aah!

20:10.839 --> 20:12.715
I was so mad at God
when I broke my leg

20:12.839 --> 20:14.925
at Shadow Ridge over Christmas break.

20:15.100 --> 20:17.603
Why?!

20:17.797 --> 20:19.674
The doctors told me
I'd have to quit sports

20:19.841 --> 20:22.344
for at least a couple
ofyears, if not forever,

20:22.538 --> 20:24.165
which meant
no first-string quarterback

20:24.321 --> 20:25.656
in the fall.

20:25.800 --> 20:27.635
It was like the end of my life.

20:27.801 --> 20:30.595
When I got back to school,
everybody was so supportive,

20:30.802 --> 20:33.596
and they all wanted to sign
my cast and everything,

20:33.803 --> 20:35.930
but I still couldn't
shake the feeling

20:36.109 --> 20:38.153
that now my life had no purpose.

20:38.327 --> 20:40.162
What did God want from me?

20:40.328 --> 20:42.622
Why did I exist?

20:42.807 --> 20:45.602
Sometimes you can search
everywhere for answers.

20:45.808 --> 20:48.144
Then one day,
destiny just walks up

20:48.330 --> 20:50.165
and taps you on the shoulder.

20:50.331 --> 20:53.125
I know because it happened to me.

20:55.159 --> 20:57.829
Paul, can I speak
to you for a minute?

20:57.986 --> 21:00.364
Mr. McAllister
changed my life.

21:00.510 --> 21:03.638
And no matter what they say
he did or did not do,

21:03.858 --> 21:06.152
I believe he is a good man.

21:06.337 --> 21:09.632
Paul, I know you've
been pretty down

21:09.861 --> 21:11.404
since your accident.

21:11.514 --> 21:14.850
Yeah. I wanted to play
football again so bad

21:15.036 --> 21:16.121
I could taste it,

21:16.211 --> 21:18.213
and maybe go on
to the playoffs and...

21:18.343 --> 21:19.261
I know.

21:19.343 --> 21:20.553
I understand disappointment.

21:20.691 --> 21:21.609
I really do.

21:21.692 --> 21:22.609
Yeah.

21:22.692 --> 21:23.735
Now, I personally think

21:23.866 --> 21:25.701
you have a very bright
future ahead of you.

21:25.867 --> 21:27.159
And I'm not talking about

21:27.302 --> 21:29.262
the fleeting glory of sports.

21:29.390 --> 21:30.766
What do you mean?

21:30.869 --> 21:32.329
Let me give you a clue.

21:32.478 --> 21:34.147
You're a natural-born leader.

21:34.305 --> 21:37.099
You're one ofthe most
popular students at Carver.

21:37.306 --> 21:38.640
You're honest,
you're straight forward,

21:38.785 --> 21:40.370
and you don't crack under pressure,

21:40.524 --> 21:42.401
as we all saw in
an amazing fourth quarter

21:42.570 --> 21:44.113
against West side.

21:44.221 --> 21:46.140
All the kids look up to you.

21:46.309 --> 21:48.020
Now, what does that spell?

21:53.834 --> 21:55.169
Student...

21:55.313 --> 21:56.689
council...

21:56.835 --> 21:58.420
president.

21:58.575 --> 22:00.160
Who, me?

22:00.316 --> 22:01.900
Oh, no. I...

22:02.056 --> 22:05.351
I don't know anything
about that stuff, Mr. M.

22:05.578 --> 22:07.664
I mean, besides,
that's Tracy Flick's thing.

22:07.840 --> 22:09.175
She's always working so hard.

22:09.319 --> 22:11.279
Yeah. She's a real
go-getter, all right.

22:11.406 --> 22:13.241
And she's super nice.

22:13.363 --> 22:14.698
Yeah, yeah,

22:14.842 --> 22:16.677
but one person assured of victory

22:16.843 --> 22:18.678
kind of undermines the whole idea

22:18.843 --> 22:20.095
of democracy, don't you think?

22:20.236 --> 22:21.154
But, Mr. M...

22:21.279 --> 22:23.156
I mean, that'd be more
like a dictatorship

22:23.281 --> 22:24.657
like we studied.

22:24.759 --> 22:25.676
But, Mr. M, there's...

22:25.759 --> 22:27.719
Paul, what's your favorite fruit?

22:27.891 --> 22:30.268
Pears.

22:30.456 --> 22:32.167
Pears. Good. OK.

22:32.284 --> 22:33.202
Let's say...

22:33.285 --> 22:35.245
Oh, no, wait.

22:35.416 --> 22:36.751
Apples.

22:36.895 --> 22:38.188
Apples.

22:38.286 --> 22:39.245
Fine.

22:39.330 --> 22:42.625
Let's say all you
ever knew were apples.

22:42.810 --> 22:45.646
Apples, apples, more apples.

22:45.812 --> 22:47.688
You might think apples
were pretty good,

22:47.812 --> 22:50.648
even if you got a rotten
one once in a while.

22:50.813 --> 22:52.189
But then one day...

22:52.292 --> 22:53.710
there's an orange.

22:53.814 --> 22:55.691
And now you can
make a decision.

22:55.814 --> 22:57.191
Do you want an apple

22:57.294 --> 22:59.170
or do you want an orange?

22:59.294 --> 23:00.962
That's democracy.

23:01.122 --> 23:03.082
I also like bananas.

23:04.297 --> 23:06.132
Exactly. Good.

23:06.253 --> 23:07.672
So what do you say?

23:07.820 --> 23:10.573
Maybe it's time to give
a little something back.

23:10.778 --> 23:12.196
How's that?

23:12.344 --> 23:13.720
I think that's...

23:13.822 --> 23:15.573
No. Just a little higher.
A little higher.

23:15.736 --> 23:16.904
Is this OK?

23:16.997 --> 23:20.084
Eric, you can't put tape
on the outside of the poster.

23:20.302 --> 23:22.137
It goes on the back
ofthe poster.

23:22.303 --> 23:24.138
You better just take
the whole thing down

23:24.304 --> 23:25.639
and redo it.

23:30.307 --> 23:34.061
Aaah-a-a-aaaah

23:41.310 --> 23:42.603
Who put you up to this?

23:42.703 --> 23:44.038
Oh, hi, Tracy.

23:44.182 --> 23:45.267
Who put you up to this?

23:45.356 --> 23:46.482
What do you mean?

23:46.618 --> 23:47.702
You just woke up this morning

23:47.836 --> 23:50.004
and suddenly decided
to run for president?

23:50.184 --> 23:53.604
No. Um, no,
I just thought that, uh...

23:53.837 --> 23:54.922
Thought what?

23:55.055 --> 23:58.142
Well, I was talking to
Mr. McAllister about my leg

23:58.361 --> 24:00.655
and how I still want to do
something for the school and...

24:00.840 --> 24:02.759
So Mr. McAllister
asked you to run.

24:02.884 --> 24:05.720
Well, um, I talked to him
and everything,

24:05.887 --> 24:07.221
but he just said that he thought

24:07.365 --> 24:08.699
it would be a good idea

24:08.844 --> 24:11.054
and how there's all different
kinds of fruits and, uh...

24:11.236 --> 24:13.405
It's nothing against you, Tracy.

24:13.541 --> 24:15.210
I mean, you're the best.

24:15.368 --> 24:17.203
Uh, I just thought, uh...

24:17.369 --> 24:18.245
OK.

24:18.369 --> 24:20.329
You're on, Mr. Popular.

24:22.284 --> 24:24.161
You might think it
upset me that Paul Metzler

24:24.284 --> 24:25.661
had decided to run against me,

24:25.763 --> 24:28.141
but nothing could be
further from the truth.

24:28.285 --> 24:29.704
He was no competition for me.

24:29.765 --> 24:31.683
It was like apples and oranges.

24:32.853 --> 24:34.646
I had to work
a little harder, that's all.

24:34.811 --> 24:36.688
You see,
I believe in the voters.

24:36.811 --> 24:37.979
They understand that elections

24:38.073 --> 24:39.866
aren't just popularity contests.

24:41.030 --> 24:42.657
They know this country was built

24:42.813 --> 24:45.649
by people just like me
who work very hard

24:45.814 --> 24:47.691
and don't have everything
handed to them

24:47.815 --> 24:49.066
on a silver spoon.

24:50.773 --> 24:53.150
Not like some rich kids
who everybody likes

24:53.295 --> 24:55.172
because their fathers
own Metzler Cement

24:55.295 --> 24:57.172
and give them trucks
on their 16th birthday

24:57.298 --> 24:59.258
and throw them big parties
all the time.

24:59.428 --> 25:01.513
No. They don't ever
have to work for anything.

25:01.689 --> 25:03.191
They think they can just,
all of a sudden,

25:03.342 --> 25:05.219
one day out ofthe blue
waltz right in

25:05.344 --> 25:06.720
with no qualifications whatsoever

25:06.822 --> 25:08.240
and try to take away

25:08.345 --> 25:09.721
what other people have worked for

25:09.823 --> 25:12.659
very, very hard their entire lives!

25:12.825 --> 25:13.742
No!

25:13.825 --> 25:15.702
Didn't bother me at all!

25:17.348 --> 25:18.725
Paul.

25:18.828 --> 25:20.162
Paul power.

25:22.307 --> 25:23.183
Paul...

25:23.308 --> 25:25.143
Paul for president.

25:25.308 --> 25:26.685
Paul for president.

25:26.787 --> 25:28.164
Promise.

25:28.309 --> 25:30.144
Progress.

25:30.310 --> 25:32.270
Peanut.

25:51.275 --> 25:53.819
There's a place I know

25:56.319 --> 25:59.698
Whereyou can look down

26:02.235 --> 26:06.072
The air makes you feel light

26:08.325 --> 26:10.160
The air makes you feel right

26:10.325 --> 26:11.201
What?

26:11.326 --> 26:13.620
I told you. I can't.

26:13.805 --> 26:16.141
It just doesn't
feel right anymore.

26:18.328 --> 26:19.704
But I love you.

26:22.504 --> 26:23.755
I said no.

26:24.853 --> 26:27.564
Hey, Tammy, guess
what happened today.

26:27.767 --> 26:29.603
Don't you fucking knock?

26:29.768 --> 26:31.895
Yeah. Oh, hi, Lisa.

26:31.986 --> 26:33.112
Get out, Paul!

26:33.248 --> 26:34.457
Listen. So Mr. McAllister,

26:34.596 --> 26:35.722
he calls me in,
and he tells me...

26:35.857 --> 26:37.108
I gotta go.

26:39.598 --> 26:40.474
You dumb shit!

26:40.598 --> 26:42.100
What'd I do?

26:42.250 --> 26:45.086
It's not like
I'm a lesbian or anything.

26:45.252 --> 26:46.629
I'm attracted to the person.

26:46.775 --> 26:49.569
It's just that all the people
I've ever been attracted to

26:49.776 --> 26:51.152
happen to be girls.

26:52.777 --> 26:54.153
Lisa, wait!

26:57.300 --> 26:58.176
Stop!

27:02.302 --> 27:03.178
What?

27:03.302 --> 27:04.637
Where you going?

27:04.781 --> 27:07.117
I'm not like you, OK?

27:07.304 --> 27:09.098
What do you mean?

27:09.217 --> 27:10.636
I'm not a dyke.

27:10.784 --> 27:12.661
And we're not in love.

27:12.785 --> 27:14.661
We were just...

27:14.785 --> 27:16.370
experimenting.

27:29.225 --> 27:32.562
How can something
that seemed so true

27:32.750 --> 27:35.586
turn out to be such a lie?

27:41.231 --> 27:44.025
Lisa and I were destined
to be together.

27:44.232 --> 27:46.609
Of all the people in the planet
who had ever lived,

27:46.754 --> 27:48.631
somehow we'd found each other.

27:48.754 --> 27:50.631
It was like a miracle.

27:53.758 --> 27:55.635
We had so much fun together,

27:55.758 --> 27:57.635
like the time we ate
a bunch of asparagus

27:57.759 --> 28:00.011
to see how long it takes
before your pee smells funny.

28:01.674 --> 28:03.175
It was very scientific.

28:03.282 --> 28:04.825
For me, it was 11 minutes.

28:04.936 --> 28:06.980
For her, it was 17.

28:08.284 --> 28:10.954
Every day I found a new way
to tell Lisa

28:11.111 --> 28:13.656
how much I loved her.

28:13.808 --> 28:15.226
"If you died right now,

28:15.374 --> 28:18.168
I would throw myself under
one of my dad's cement trucks

28:18.375 --> 28:21.044
and get poured into your tomb."

28:23.769 --> 28:26.063
But it just seemed
like the closer we got,

28:26.248 --> 28:28.041
the more she pulled away.

28:28.205 --> 28:29.831
Are you crazy?

28:29.988 --> 28:30.864
What?

28:30.988 --> 28:32.114
These are private.
These are for us.

28:32.250 --> 28:33.209
So?

28:33.295 --> 28:35.046
But other people
can see them, too.

28:35.164 --> 28:36.457
I don't care.

28:36.600 --> 28:38.143
Well, I do.

28:41.297 --> 28:44.092
What did I do
to make her change?

28:45.777 --> 28:47.153
What's wrong with me?

28:50.301 --> 28:52.136
Sometimes when I'm sad,

28:52.301 --> 28:55.096
I sit and watch
the power station.

28:55.303 --> 28:58.556
They say if you lie between
2 of the main wires,

28:58.783 --> 29:00.618
your body just evaporates.

29:00.783 --> 29:02.619
You become a gas.

29:02.784 --> 29:05.620
I wonder what that
would feel like.

29:12.832 --> 29:14.667
I don't know why,

29:14.832 --> 29:17.627
but Lisa decided
she wanted to hurt me.

29:17.833 --> 29:20.628
And she knew exactly what to do.

29:22.966 --> 29:25.135
I sure was surprised
the day Lisa Flanagan

29:25.314 --> 29:28.484
asked me for a ride home
and ended up blowing me.

29:29.838 --> 29:32.132
I've wanted this for so long.

29:33.535 --> 29:35.829
I mean, life is so weird.

29:36.014 --> 29:38.642
First, Lisa has a big fight
with my sister,

29:38.841 --> 29:42.428
and the next thing you know,
she's my girlfriend.

29:42.669 --> 29:45.171
Since Lisa knew all about
public relations and stuff,

29:45.366 --> 29:47.701
she offered to help me
with my campaign.

29:47.888 --> 29:49.681
We made a great team.

29:49.845 --> 29:52.640
It seemed so natural,
the two of us together.

29:52.846 --> 29:54.682
It was like a miracle.

29:57.240 --> 29:59.659
My leg wasn't bugging me too much

29:59.849 --> 30:01.226
and the weather was so nice.

30:01.372 --> 30:02.749
And every day after school

30:02.851 --> 30:06.647
Lisa and I would go to her house
to fuck and have a hot tub.

30:26.295 --> 30:28.172
If that's the way
they wanted it,

30:28.296 --> 30:30.047
then that's the way
it was gonna be.

30:30.210 --> 30:32.629
But I wasn't going down
without a fight.

30:39.344 --> 30:40.261
Tammy?

30:42.344 --> 30:44.555
Tammy, what are you doing?

30:44.736 --> 30:46.655
You're the advisor.
You should stop her.

30:46.824 --> 30:48.618
She's not qualified.
She's just a sophomore.

30:48.782 --> 30:49.700
Did you know that?

30:49.825 --> 30:51.535
Calm down, Tracy.
Just calm down.

30:51.652 --> 30:53.195
We can't both run, can we?

30:53.349 --> 30:54.600
I mean, we're brother and sister.

30:54.740 --> 30:55.741
Can we?

30:55.871 --> 30:57.748
It's a conflict of interest,
and Paul was first.

30:57.916 --> 31:00.210
Anybody who gets signatures
in on time can run,

31:00.352 --> 31:02.229
and she got in
just under the wire.

31:04.353 --> 31:06.522
These are a bunch of burnouts.

31:06.658 --> 31:08.702
And what's this one?
It's illegible.

31:08.877 --> 31:10.128
I can't even read that.

31:10.268 --> 31:12.187
That's Tim... Cobsa.

31:12.356 --> 31:14.734
She's doing this
to get back at me.

31:14.878 --> 31:15.796
For what?

31:15.879 --> 31:18.214
I mean, at you.

31:18.358 --> 31:19.776
For what?

31:19.881 --> 31:21.674
Tim Cobsa?

31:21.838 --> 31:24.716
Tim Cobsa? Who's he?
I've never even heard of him.

31:24.926 --> 31:26.678
Look, why don't we
just forget about Tammy?

31:26.840 --> 31:28.217
We'll have the assembly tomorrow.

31:28.319 --> 31:29.696
Everybody can make their speeches,

31:29.841 --> 31:32.177
and I'm sure everything's
gonna be just fine.

31:32.451 --> 31:33.243
Hey! Whee!

31:33.364 --> 31:35.658
Jim, don't.
You're scaring him.

31:35.844 --> 31:37.637
Nah. He likes it.

31:37.801 --> 31:38.718
Not that much.

31:38.845 --> 31:40.221
Around that time,

31:40.366 --> 31:42.202
Diane and I were
hanging out a lot

31:42.368 --> 31:43.536
at Linda Novotny's house,

31:43.630 --> 31:45.673
giving her our love and support

31:45.848 --> 31:49.226
and helping her make it
through a difficult time.

31:54.373 --> 31:56.708
Diane really wanted to have kids,

31:56.852 --> 31:58.103
and so did I,

31:58.201 --> 32:00.662
but it seemed like there
was always a reason to wait:

32:00.853 --> 32:02.688
She had to finish
nursing school,

32:02.854 --> 32:04.230
I had to get my master's,

32:04.376 --> 32:07.171
we needed a new house,
we needed more money.

32:07.377 --> 32:09.504
Finally, we just decided
to go for it.

32:09.769 --> 32:11.021
You gonna do it?

32:11.118 --> 32:12.495
You gonna do it?

32:12.597 --> 32:15.642
And for over a year,
we hadn't had any luck.

32:15.858 --> 32:18.152
Come on. Do it. Do it.

32:18.338 --> 32:20.173
Fill me up. Come on.

32:20.296 --> 32:22.173
Fill me up.

32:22.296 --> 32:23.673
Fill me up.

32:31.778 --> 32:32.695
OK.

32:38.303 --> 32:39.221
Good job.

32:47.306 --> 32:48.432
Say, Jim?

32:50.046 --> 32:51.464
Jim, can you get this?

32:51.613 --> 32:52.739
I can't.

32:52.831 --> 32:54.207
Oh, yeah, sure.

32:54.309 --> 32:56.186
Just put it on the table.

32:56.310 --> 32:57.228
All right.

33:01.791 --> 33:02.750
Without Dave around,

33:02.877 --> 33:04.712
Linda needed a lot of help
around the house.

33:04.834 --> 33:06.377
Where do you want it, here?

33:06.487 --> 33:07.405
No.

33:08.835 --> 33:10.212
More this way.

33:11.838 --> 33:13.381
Here?

33:13.490 --> 33:15.742
Uh, yeah. That's good.

33:18.884 --> 33:22.095
I had always liked Linda,
but we'd never had a chance

33:22.320 --> 33:24.697
to spend any time
alone together.

33:24.842 --> 33:26.802
Oughta warm you up a little bit.

33:26.974 --> 33:28.183
Now with Dave
out of the picture,

33:28.322 --> 33:30.157
I began to see what
an incredibly sensitive

33:30.322 --> 33:33.367
and giving person she was.

33:33.541 --> 33:35.918
We got to be
kind of like buddies.

33:36.065 --> 33:37.191
I even took her to the mall
one time

33:37.326 --> 33:39.245
while her car was in the shop.

33:42.328 --> 33:43.746
What do you think?

33:45.329 --> 33:46.914
You look great.

33:47.068 --> 33:49.654
I can't afford this stuff right now.

33:49.851 --> 33:51.603
Ah, come on.
You've had a hard year.

33:51.723 --> 33:53.683
You're cooped up
all the time with the kid.

33:53.854 --> 33:55.147
Let go. Live a little.

33:55.289 --> 33:56.165
You sure?

33:56.289 --> 33:57.165
Yeah.

33:59.856 --> 34:01.691
So what do you think?

34:01.857 --> 34:03.191
Should we get a room?

34:03.336 --> 34:04.712
Should we get a what?

34:17.862 --> 34:19.197
That's not funny.

34:27.301 --> 34:29.178
How'd it go?

34:29.303 --> 34:30.219
Fine.

34:30.303 --> 34:31.221
You know...

34:31.303 --> 34:33.179
just went to Westerly's.

34:33.304 --> 34:35.097
Did you guys have fun?

34:36.784 --> 34:38.202
Um...

34:38.304 --> 34:39.223
yeah.

34:39.306 --> 34:41.766
No, I mean... you know.

34:41.958 --> 34:44.295
What?

34:44.438 --> 34:46.690
Well, Linda's great,

34:46.831 --> 34:49.501
but she can be
a little bit much sometimes.

34:51.833 --> 34:53.083
Yeah.

34:53.224 --> 34:55.643
Oh, God.
Oh, just like that.

