01:18:33.853 --> 01:18:35.855
Yeah?

01:18:36.028 --> 01:18:38.280
I think we have a problem.

01:18:38.420 --> 01:18:41.632
253, 254, and 255.

01:18:41.856 --> 01:18:43.358
Yep, I get the same as you, Jim.

01:18:43.509 --> 01:18:45.302
Looks like Paul's
our next president.

01:18:45.423 --> 01:18:46.925
No way!

01:18:47.031 --> 01:18:48.408
It doesn't make sense.

01:18:48.555 --> 01:18:50.891
Well, sorry, Larry,
but my fiigures work out

01:18:51.077 --> 01:18:52.579
exactly the same
as Mr. McAllister's.

01:18:52.729 --> 01:18:56.983
I get, uh, 256 for Paul,
255 forTracy.

01:18:57.254 --> 01:19:00.299
And 290 disregards, right?

01:19:00.516 --> 01:19:01.475
If you say so.

01:19:01.603 --> 01:19:03.480
Mostly Tammy fans,
if you can believe it.

01:19:03.603 --> 01:19:04.980
See? It doesn't add up.

01:19:05.082 --> 01:19:08.377
There were 801 ballots,
but 803 people voted.

01:19:08.562 --> 01:19:09.730
Well, there must
be 2 votes missing.

01:19:09.867 --> 01:19:10.993
Check the register.

01:19:11.085 --> 01:19:13.087
He's right. 2 people must
have pocketed their ballots.

01:19:13.259 --> 01:19:14.803
Usually there's more.

01:19:14.956 --> 01:19:18.585
But they were there.
I counted 803 votes.

01:19:18.827 --> 01:19:21.121
It happens, Larry.
People make mistakes.

01:19:21.263 --> 01:19:22.806
I didn't make a mistake.

01:19:22.916 --> 01:19:25.085
Every vote was there
when you sat down.

01:19:25.264 --> 01:19:27.767
Easy, Falch. I don't
like where you're going.

01:19:27.961 --> 01:19:29.254
I'm sorry, Dr. Hendricks,

01:19:29.396 --> 01:19:31.398
but every vote
was accounted for.

01:19:31.572 --> 01:19:32.990
Falch, that's enough.

01:19:33.094 --> 01:19:35.304
End of story.

01:19:56.363 --> 01:19:57.573
Paul?

01:19:57.668 --> 01:20:00.671
I just want to let you know
that no matter what happens

01:20:00.887 --> 01:20:01.846
and how this turns out,

01:20:01.975 --> 01:20:04.019
you've run a really great campaign.

01:20:04.193 --> 01:20:05.695
Good luck.

01:20:05.802 --> 01:20:08.346
Well, thanks, Tracy.
You, too.

01:20:08.542 --> 01:20:10.627
I'm just glad it's over.

01:20:12.588 --> 01:20:14.048
If we can just get started.

01:20:14.153 --> 01:20:16.656
People. People.

01:20:16.850 --> 01:20:18.352
As soon as the winners
are announced,

01:20:18.502 --> 01:20:20.212
we can all go home, OK?

01:20:20.330 --> 01:20:23.249
Some contests are...

01:20:23.462 --> 01:20:26.548
are so well-fought
that it seems unfair

01:20:26.767 --> 01:20:27.851
for someone to win...

01:20:27.984 --> 01:20:31.321
Act surprised.
Walk slowly to the podium.

01:20:31.508 --> 01:20:34.845
Be modest. Thank them
for this incredible honor.

01:20:35.075 --> 01:20:37.244
They're all highly qualifiied

01:20:37.423 --> 01:20:41.844
and embody the, uh,
integrity that we expect

01:20:42.121 --> 01:20:44.331
from the school leadership.

01:20:44.513 --> 01:20:46.264
That said, the whole point
of an election

01:20:46.382 --> 01:20:48.843
is to chose a winner,
and that you have done.

01:20:48.993 --> 01:20:51.370
We'll begin with president.

01:20:51.516 --> 01:20:53.518
I'djust like to add

01:20:53.690 --> 01:20:55.734
that this was
an extraordinarily close race.

01:20:57.866 --> 01:21:00.369
It is my pleasure
to announce the next president

01:21:00.518 --> 01:21:02.937
of George Washington Carver
High School...

01:21:03.085 --> 01:21:05.546
Paul Metzler.

01:21:18.699 --> 01:21:20.535
Jeez, you guys, thanks.

01:21:22.440 --> 01:21:24.734
Wow! Thanks.

01:21:24.876 --> 01:21:26.544
I promise to do my best

01:21:26.703 --> 01:21:30.790
and do a really good job
and be a good president.

01:21:31.053 --> 01:21:33.221
I just want to thank,
uh, Lisa Flanagan

01:21:33.402 --> 01:21:34.653
for being a super campaign manager.

01:21:34.750 --> 01:21:37.711
I'd also like to say...

01:22:17.592 --> 01:22:19.343
It's Mr. M.

01:22:19.463 --> 01:22:22.383
Yes, over there. Yeah, come on.

01:22:26.075 --> 01:22:28.369
Wow, Mr. M.
This is so wild.

01:22:28.509 --> 01:22:30.053
We were just here, uh, you know,

01:22:30.206 --> 01:22:31.582
celebrating my victory,
and you're here.

01:22:31.684 --> 01:22:33.060
This is incredible.
This is great.

01:22:33.207 --> 01:22:34.583
Well, these are my parents.

01:22:34.685 --> 01:22:35.811
Hi, Dick Metzler.

01:22:35.948 --> 01:22:36.823
Jim McAllister.

01:22:36.948 --> 01:22:38.241
- Jo Metzler.
- How do you do?

01:22:38.382 --> 01:22:39.842
Paul just thinks
the world ofyou.

01:22:39.949 --> 01:22:40.908
I mean, you should hear him.

01:22:40.993 --> 01:22:42.244
He goes on and on and on.

01:22:42.341 --> 01:22:43.258
Yeah, apparently
you've really

01:22:43.386 --> 01:22:44.595
come behind him,
really helped him out

01:22:44.734 --> 01:22:45.860
with that student
council thing and all.

01:22:45.951 --> 01:22:48.412
Oh, well... well, Paul
doesn't need any help from me.

01:22:48.605 --> 01:22:50.732
He's... He's going places.
You should be very proud.

01:22:50.909 --> 01:22:51.785
Oh, we are.

01:22:51.910 --> 01:22:53.578
Hey, look, you're all alone.

01:22:53.737 --> 01:22:55.072
Why don't you come
over and join us?

01:22:55.172 --> 01:22:56.089
Yeah. Yeah, come on.

01:22:56.172 --> 01:22:57.799
Oh, I'm just fiinishing up here.

01:22:57.956 --> 01:22:59.249
I've gotta get home.

01:22:59.479 --> 01:23:00.688
Oh, well, uh,

01:23:00.827 --> 01:23:03.913
why don't you guys
go sit down, and, uh...

01:23:04.133 --> 01:23:05.884
you know, I'll catch up
with you in a minute.

01:23:06.002 --> 01:23:07.879
I'm going to talk to Mr. M
about some important stuff,

01:23:08.003 --> 01:23:08.920
all right?

01:23:09.003 --> 01:23:10.296
All right.
That sounds great.

01:23:10.396 --> 01:23:12.272
- Hey, sure nice to meet you.
- Great to meet you.

01:23:12.396 --> 01:23:13.898
- Pleasure.
- So nice, and thank you.

01:23:14.049 --> 01:23:15.384
You bet.

01:23:19.487 --> 01:23:21.072
So, Mr. M, I was starting
to think about,

01:23:21.226 --> 01:23:23.270
you know, some ideas
for what we could do.

01:23:23.444 --> 01:23:25.071
I was thinking
it would be cool

01:23:25.227 --> 01:23:26.145
to have a carnival.

01:23:26.227 --> 01:23:27.771
You know, with rides and stuff.

01:23:27.924 --> 01:23:30.009
And it could be for,
like, muscular dystrophy.

01:23:30.186 --> 01:23:33.272
And then on Halloween,
a haunted house.

01:23:33.491 --> 01:23:35.159
You know, a really
good haunted house,

01:23:35.318 --> 01:23:36.570
not those cheesy bad ones.

01:23:36.709 --> 01:23:37.752
You know, I mean,

01:23:37.884 --> 01:23:39.678
this one would be super-scary.

01:23:39.841 --> 01:23:41.551
And then for home coming,

01:23:41.713 --> 01:23:43.256
well, you know
how last year's theme

01:23:43.365 --> 01:23:45.784
was " Heaven On Earth"?
Well, this year...

01:23:45.975 --> 01:23:49.520
Paul, we'll have plenty of
time to talk about this later.

01:23:49.759 --> 01:23:52.303
A whole year, in fact.

01:23:52.498 --> 01:23:54.876
But right now, I'djust...

01:23:55.065 --> 01:23:57.150
I need to fiinish my pie,

01:23:57.327 --> 01:23:59.204
go on home.

01:23:59.371 --> 01:24:02.541
Yeah, OK. Sorry.

01:24:02.721 --> 01:24:05.599
Uh, Mr. M,
just one more thing.

01:24:05.808 --> 01:24:09.312
So, uh, do you think
Tracy's gonna be OK?

01:24:09.505 --> 01:24:11.841
I mean, I saw her face
after the assembly.

01:24:12.027 --> 01:24:14.238
It looked like she was
taking it pretty hard.

01:24:14.420 --> 01:24:16.756
Don't worry about Tracy.

01:24:16.942 --> 01:24:19.653
She'll be fiine.

01:24:33.254 --> 01:24:35.006
Oh, sweetheart.

01:24:37.952 --> 01:24:40.871
Oh, baby. Baby.

01:24:41.040 --> 01:24:42.792
Oh, baby.

01:24:42.953 --> 01:24:45.038
Take one of my pills.

01:24:45.216 --> 01:24:48.010
You'll feel better.

01:24:48.217 --> 01:24:50.177
Here.

01:24:53.522 --> 01:24:57.109
Come on, baby. Come on.

01:24:57.307 --> 01:25:00.935
Lie down. Lie down.

01:25:01.178 --> 01:25:04.306
That's a good girl.
Lie down.

01:25:04.527 --> 01:25:07.155
Good girl.

01:25:07.353 --> 01:25:09.230
That's... That's it.

01:25:09.355 --> 01:25:11.023
That's it, baby.

01:25:11.138 --> 01:25:13.390
That's it, honey.

01:25:18.010 --> 01:25:21.096
Maybe you needed
more posters, honey.

01:25:21.317 --> 01:25:24.445
Or if you'djust
taken my suggestions

01:25:24.665 --> 01:25:26.375
about your speech.

01:25:26.492 --> 01:25:28.786
I don't know.

01:25:28.971 --> 01:25:30.848
We'll fiigure it out.

01:25:42.629 --> 01:25:44.464
Diane.

01:25:44.629 --> 01:25:47.883
I... I made a mistake and I...

01:25:55.851 --> 01:25:57.978
Did you want the same room?

01:25:59.984 --> 01:26:01.610
Yeah, OK.

01:26:29.385 --> 01:26:31.262
It's a beautiful day

01:26:31.430 --> 01:26:33.307
The next day, I woke up

01:26:33.430 --> 01:26:35.516
resolved to get
my life back on track.

01:26:35.693 --> 01:26:38.571
The way I saw it, Diane's
kicking me out of the house

01:26:38.780 --> 01:26:39.865
had been a good thing,

01:26:39.999 --> 01:26:41.250
a wake-up call.

01:26:41.391 --> 01:26:44.394
It wasn't a setback.
It was an opportunity.

01:26:44.567 --> 01:26:46.527
I fiigured we just
needed a little time

01:26:46.697 --> 01:26:48.366
to work things out.

01:26:48.524 --> 01:26:50.693
The election was behind me,

01:26:50.872 --> 01:26:53.041
and the worst was over.

01:26:53.222 --> 01:26:55.307
After all, what harm
had really been done?

01:26:55.440 --> 01:26:57.233
Nobody was dead.

01:27:02.747 --> 01:27:03.664
Jim?
Jim?!

01:27:03.747 --> 01:27:04.665
Yeah.

01:27:04.747 --> 01:27:06.249
Walt wants to seeyou.

01:27:06.400 --> 01:27:08.444
OK, thanks.

01:27:19.928 --> 01:27:21.804
You r... rang?

01:27:25.104 --> 01:27:26.480
Mr. McAllister,

01:27:26.626 --> 01:27:29.086
I hope you can help us
clear something up.

01:28:08.120 --> 01:28:09.372
- Yo?
- Pierdo.

01:28:09.512 --> 01:28:11.306
- Tu?
- Pierdes.

01:28:11.469 --> 01:28:13.179
El, ella, usted?

01:28:13.339 --> 01:28:14.215
Pierde.

01:28:14.340 --> 01:28:15.508
Nosotros?

01:28:15.645 --> 01:28:17.146
Pierdemos.

01:28:17.298 --> 01:28:18.633
Gracias.

01:28:21.343 --> 01:28:23.220
Señor Presidente.

01:28:23.343 --> 01:28:26.930
Quieren verte enla ofiicina.

01:28:27.172 --> 01:28:29.090
Huh?

01:28:30.259 --> 01:28:31.635
Dr. Hendricks?

01:28:35.260 --> 01:28:37.137
Uh, come on in, son.
We have something...

01:28:37.261 --> 01:28:40.347
hard we have to tell you.

01:28:40.524 --> 01:28:41.442
Is it about Tammy?

01:28:41.524 --> 01:28:42.901
It's about the election.

01:28:46.570 --> 01:28:49.406
After Paul
got the bad news,

01:28:49.570 --> 01:28:51.572
Walt asked for a few minutes
alone with me.

01:28:51.702 --> 01:28:54.246
It was very simple, really.

01:28:54.399 --> 01:28:56.318
I offered my resignation,

01:28:56.443 --> 01:28:58.904
and he accepted.

01:28:59.097 --> 01:29:02.558
Very quietly, it was
all over for Jim McAllister

01:29:02.750 --> 01:29:04.168
at Carver High.

01:29:08.057 --> 01:29:10.517
Suddenly everyone knew who I was...

01:29:10.710 --> 01:29:12.086
that corrupt teacher

01:29:12.232 --> 01:29:14.859
who had tried to crush
the dreams of an innocent girl.

01:29:15.015 --> 01:29:17.893
Overnight, all the good things
I had ever done in my life

01:29:18.104 --> 01:29:20.398
evaporated.

01:29:20.584 --> 01:29:23.086
Soon the wire services
picked up on the story.

01:29:23.237 --> 01:29:26.573
It was the kind of absurd news item
people E-mail each other

01:29:26.803 --> 01:29:29.764
or post on the bulletin
board at work.

01:29:29.979 --> 01:29:33.857
To top it all off, Diane had
started divorce proceedings.

01:29:34.110 --> 01:29:37.071
She was completely unforgiving
about the thing with Linda.

01:29:37.285 --> 01:29:39.829
In the end, she took
almost everything,

01:29:40.025 --> 01:29:41.735
including the house.

01:29:41.896 --> 01:29:43.898
I got the car.

01:30:00.164 --> 01:30:01.999
Then one day,

01:30:02.121 --> 01:30:04.165
I realized it was time
to get out of Omaha

01:30:04.296 --> 01:30:05.923
and move on.

01:30:12.255 --> 01:30:13.631
Senior year was great.

01:30:13.778 --> 01:30:17.615
Sure, I didn't get to
play ball or be president,

01:30:17.823 --> 01:30:20.993
but I got elected
homecoming king and prom king.

01:30:21.172 --> 01:30:23.550
I got into Nebraska,
like I wanted,

01:30:23.738 --> 01:30:25.073
and early rushed PhiDelts.

01:30:25.173 --> 01:30:26.967
And at the end of the year,
me and my buddies

01:30:27.130 --> 01:30:30.258
threw a bitchin' Mexican party
down at the cement plant.

01:30:30.480 --> 01:30:32.690
Shit, that was a good party.

01:30:32.915 --> 01:30:36.335
The only really bad thing
about senior year was Lisa.

01:30:36.569 --> 01:30:38.154
Right before Christmas,
she dumped me.

01:30:38.308 --> 01:30:40.477
One minute, she's
totally in love with me,

01:30:40.658 --> 01:30:44.411
and then boom, she goes after
my football buddy Randy.

01:30:44.659 --> 01:30:46.953
Sometimes I wonder
what would have happened

01:30:47.138 --> 01:30:48.932
if I had actually won
the election.

01:30:49.096 --> 01:30:50.639
Maybe my whole life
would be different.

01:30:50.793 --> 01:30:53.629
Like I might never
have gone to Yosemite

01:30:53.794 --> 01:30:55.504
with Greg and Travis.

01:30:55.619 --> 01:30:57.580
Or maybe I'd be dead.

01:30:57.751 --> 01:31:00.587
Alleluia

01:31:00.796 --> 01:31:02.714
Catholic school
was great.

01:31:04.667 --> 01:31:07.920
I mean, the teachers
kind of sucked,

01:31:08.104 --> 01:31:10.523
and they were supposedly
way more strict.

01:31:10.669 --> 01:31:13.005
But you could get away
with murder.

01:31:13.192 --> 01:31:16.028
The best thing
about Immaculate Heart

01:31:16.193 --> 01:31:18.321
was meeting Jennifer.

01:31:18.455 --> 01:31:22.251
JenniferJuniper

01:31:22.456 --> 01:31:25.543
Lives up on the hill

01:31:25.762 --> 01:31:29.641
JenniferJuniper

01:31:29.895 --> 01:31:32.105
Sitting very still

01:31:33.331 --> 01:31:35.207
Is she sleeping

01:31:35.331 --> 01:31:36.707
Jennifer and I
are soul mates

01:31:36.853 --> 01:31:39.939
and we're never, ever,
ever going to be apart.

01:31:40.160 --> 01:31:44.289
JenniferJuniper

01:31:44.509 --> 01:31:47.678
Order! Order. Order!

01:31:47.902 --> 01:31:49.570
Senior year was
very productive for me.

01:31:49.728 --> 01:31:51.229
Let's vote on this issue.

01:31:51.380 --> 01:31:53.132
On top of a very successful
student council year,

01:31:53.295 --> 01:31:55.422
I was in the top
seventh percentile

01:31:55.600 --> 01:31:56.768
of my graduating class.

01:31:56.861 --> 01:31:57.903
Opposed?

01:31:58.036 --> 01:31:59.245
And I got into Georgetown,
like I wanted,

01:31:59.340 --> 01:32:01.717
with scholarships.

01:32:01.906 --> 01:32:03.241
Approved.

01:32:05.082 --> 01:32:08.168
But sometimes I got lonely,
and I'd think about Dave.

01:32:08.345 --> 01:32:09.846
I missed our talks.

01:32:09.997 --> 01:32:12.332
Maybe it could have
worked out between us.

01:32:12.519 --> 01:32:13.603
I don't know.

01:32:13.737 --> 01:32:16.573
I wonder what he's doing now.

01:32:16.782 --> 01:32:20.703
Maybe he fiinally
fiinished his novel.

01:32:20.958 --> 01:32:25.212
But you know, even with
all my my riad accomplishments

01:32:25.438 --> 01:32:27.023
and bright future,

01:32:27.177 --> 01:32:29.930
somehow I just didn't feel
the way you're supposed to feel.

01:32:30.136 --> 01:32:32.054
Everybody else seemed so happy,

01:32:32.223 --> 01:32:36.477
planning big parties and
signing each other's yearbooks.

01:32:36.745 --> 01:32:38.789
Hardly anybody signed mine.

01:32:38.964 --> 01:32:40.800
You'd think as
student body president,

01:32:40.966 --> 01:32:42.509
I'd be the one
surrounded by friends.

01:32:42.662 --> 01:32:44.914
But it wasn't like that at all.

01:32:48.837 --> 01:32:51.590
Brittany Blake Fillmore.

01:32:51.795 --> 01:32:53.505
As far as
Mr. McAllister was concerned,

01:32:53.666 --> 01:32:56.335
you might be surprised,
but I hardly thought about him

01:32:56.537 --> 01:32:57.621
at all anymore.

01:32:57.754 --> 01:33:00.507
Besides, nobody had heard
from him in a long time.

01:33:00.712 --> 01:33:04.007
It was almost like he'd never
existed in the fiirst place.

01:33:04.236 --> 01:33:06.864
Tracy Enid Flick.

01:33:09.063 --> 01:33:11.398
When I got to Georgetown,

01:33:11.586 --> 01:33:14.005
I thought I'd fiinally be
among people who were like me.

01:33:14.195 --> 01:33:16.447
You know, smarter,
more ambitious people.

01:33:16.588 --> 01:33:19.216
I was sure that fiinally
I'd make some true friends.

01:33:20.807 --> 01:33:22.559
Excuse me!

01:33:22.720 --> 01:33:24.722
Would you please be quiet?!

01:33:24.895 --> 01:33:26.939
It wasn't like that at all.

01:33:27.114 --> 01:33:28.865
A lot of them were just
spoiled little rich kids

01:33:29.028 --> 01:33:31.530
who didn't know
how lucky they had it.

01:33:31.725 --> 01:33:34.895
That's OK. I've come to
accept that very few people

01:33:35.117 --> 01:33:36.785
are truly destined to be special,

01:33:36.944 --> 01:33:38.654
and we're solo fliers.

01:33:38.770 --> 01:33:40.939
I guess it really is
like Dave said,

01:33:41.120 --> 01:33:44.164
"If you're gonna be great,
you've got to be lonely."

01:33:48.818 --> 01:33:52.906
What happens to a man
when he loses everything?

01:33:53.123 --> 01:33:55.375
Everything he's worked for.

01:33:55.559 --> 01:33:59.521
Everything he believes in.

01:33:59.779 --> 01:34:01.906
Driven from his home,

01:34:02.084 --> 01:34:04.378
cast out of society,

01:34:04.564 --> 01:34:06.482
how can he survive?

01:34:06.651 --> 01:34:08.027
Where can he go?

01:34:08.172 --> 01:34:11.050
Right this way.

01:34:11.262 --> 01:34:12.847
New York City.

01:34:22.265 --> 01:34:25.226
For centuries, people
have come to New York

01:34:25.441 --> 01:34:28.777
seeking refuge from
their troubled lives.

01:34:29.008 --> 01:34:32.511
Now I am one of them.

01:34:32.705 --> 01:34:34.623
Besides, I'd always dreamed
of living in New York.

01:34:34.749 --> 01:34:36.793
All that excitement and culture.

01:34:36.967 --> 01:34:39.720
Living in the city brings
surprises all the time.

01:34:39.882 --> 01:34:42.551
Once in a while, I even bump
into former students of mine

01:34:42.708 --> 01:34:44.668
from Carver.

01:34:44.839 --> 01:34:47.300
Oh, sure, my apartment's
a little smaller

01:34:47.493 --> 01:34:49.078
than what I was used to
back in Omaha,

01:34:49.233 --> 01:34:51.026
and the rent's pretty darn steep,

01:34:51.190 --> 01:34:52.691
but it's got a lot of character.

01:34:52.843 --> 01:34:54.595
And I'm cozy enough.

01:34:57.758 --> 01:34:59.760
Besides, it's great
not needing a car.

01:34:59.890 --> 01:35:02.809
And I get a lot of reading
done on the subway.

01:35:03.021 --> 01:35:05.106
Some days I even walk to work.

01:35:07.501 --> 01:35:10.337
The job market is
pretty tight in New York,

01:35:10.545 --> 01:35:12.756
but after hunting around
for a while,

01:35:12.893 --> 01:35:15.271
I fiinally landed a position
in the education department

01:35:15.416 --> 01:35:17.544
at the Museum of Natural History.

01:35:17.722 --> 01:35:20.600
That's right.
I'm teaching again.

01:35:20.810 --> 01:35:24.105
When a school brings
its students to the museum

01:35:24.334 --> 01:35:25.293
on a fiield trip,

01:35:25.420 --> 01:35:27.297
there's a staffof
both volunteer docents

01:35:27.465 --> 01:35:29.342
and trained educators like myself...

01:35:29.465 --> 01:35:32.677
who pick up where
the classwork leaves off.

01:35:32.859 --> 01:35:34.986
And I've started
seeing someone new.

01:35:35.163 --> 01:35:37.082
Her name is Jillian.

01:35:37.251 --> 01:35:39.920
She works at the museum, too,
in Signs and Signage.

01:35:40.078 --> 01:35:42.706
She's really different
from Diane, and, I don't know,

01:35:42.906 --> 01:35:45.158
I've never met anyone
quite like her.

01:35:45.342 --> 01:35:47.969
She just got out of
a long relationship, too,

01:35:48.169 --> 01:35:49.796
so we're trying
to take it slow.

01:35:53.823 --> 01:35:56.284
You might ask if I ever
saw Tracy Flick again.

01:35:56.432 --> 01:35:58.143
Well, I did.

01:35:58.259 --> 01:36:00.220
Just once.

01:36:00.390 --> 01:36:05.353
I was down in Washington for
a museum educator's conference,

01:36:05.654 --> 01:36:07.906
and I stayed an extra day
to do some sightseeing.

01:36:10.656 --> 01:36:13.617
After an inspiring morning
on the Mall,

01:36:13.788 --> 01:36:17.458
I was on my way to
the Holocaust Museum when...

01:36:52.411 --> 01:36:54.538
I'll never know ifshe saw me.

01:36:54.673 --> 01:36:56.216
Probably not.

01:36:56.370 --> 01:36:58.747
But in that moment,
all the bad memories,

01:36:58.935 --> 01:37:01.813
all the things I'd ever
wanted to say to her,

01:37:02.024 --> 01:37:04.193
it all came flooding back.

01:37:07.025 --> 01:37:09.069
My fiirst impulse
was to run over there,

01:37:09.243 --> 01:37:10.453
pound on her window,

01:37:10.549 --> 01:37:12.842
and demand that she admit
she tore down those posters

01:37:13.027 --> 01:37:16.197
and lied and cheated her way
into winning that election.

01:37:16.420 --> 01:37:21.342
But, instead,
I just stood there.

01:37:21.639 --> 01:37:26.060
And I suddenly realized
I wasn't angry at her anymore.

01:37:26.337 --> 01:37:29.048
I just felt sorry for her.

01:37:29.251 --> 01:37:31.295
I mean, when I think
about my new life

01:37:31.469 --> 01:37:33.722
and all the exciting
things I'm doing,

01:37:33.906 --> 01:37:36.617
and then I think about
what her life must be like...

01:37:36.820 --> 01:37:39.323
probably still getting up
at 5:00 in the morning

01:37:39.515 --> 01:37:41.768
to pursue her pathetic
little dreams...

01:37:41.952 --> 01:37:44.454
it just makes me sad.

01:37:44.649 --> 01:37:47.986
I mean where is she really
trying to get to anyway?

01:37:48.216 --> 01:37:50.844
What is she doing in that limo?

01:37:51.042 --> 01:37:54.212
Who the fuck does
she think she is?!

01:38:03.134 --> 01:38:06.346
Hey, you! Hey!

01:38:06.570 --> 01:38:08.614
You asshole!

01:38:08.745 --> 01:38:10.998
But that's all
ancient history now.

01:38:11.181 --> 01:38:13.558
I've got a whole new life.

01:38:13.704 --> 01:38:15.998
I mean, that's what's
great about America.

01:38:16.182 --> 01:38:17.517
You can always start over.

01:38:17.619 --> 01:38:19.788
So would that make this
an igneous rock

01:38:19.923 --> 01:38:22.092
